https://angular.io/guide/template-syntax
template: `
  <h1>{{title}}</h1>
  <h2>My favorite hero is: {{myHero}}</h2>
  `The template is a multi-line string within ECMAScript 2015 backticks (`). The backtick (`)—which is not the same character as a single quote (')—
  allows you to compose a string over several lines, which makes the HTML more readable.
  
  In Angular, the component plays the part of the controller/viewmodel, and the template represents the view.
  Some legal HTML doesn't make much sense in a template. The <html>, <body>, and <base> elements have no useful role. 
  You can extend the HTML vocabulary of your templates with components and directives that appear as new elements and attributes. 
  Almost all HTML syntax is valid template syntax. The <script> element is a notable exception; it is forbidden, eliminating the risk of script injection attacks. In practice, <script> 
  is ignored and a warning appears in the browser console. See the Security page for details.
  
  Interpolation ( {{...}} )
  <p>The sum of 1 + 1 is not {{1 + 1 + getVal()}}</p>
  The expression can invoke methods of the host component such as getVal(), seen here:
  
  Types of bindings:
  https://angular.io/guide/template-syntax#binding-syntax-an-overview
  
  HTML attribute vs. DOM property
  https://angular.io/guide/template-syntax#html-attribute-vs-dom-property
  
